T1  - The Resources Management Movement (The Coming Death of Production Management Education)
AU  - Schonberger, Richard J.
Y1  - 1972/09/01
PY  - 1972
DA  - 1972/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/254866
DO  - 10.5465/254866
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 382
EP  - 385
VL  - 15
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article discusses the problems associate with students' attitudes toward production management courses in business education. According to the author, students view these courses in negative light, often confusing them with manufacturing courses, when many of them do not to be involved in manufacturing industries. He suggests several ways that educators can encourage more students to take these courses since they are important to the future generations of managers. One of the ways that is suggested is having textbooks de-emphasize the role of manufacturing in production management. He then calls for the name of the courses to be called ?resource management,? since production has more to do with managing resources.
AB  - The article discusses the problems associate with students' attitudes toward production management courses in business education. According to the author, students view these courses in negative light, often confusing them with manufacturing courses, when many of them do not to be involved in manufacturing industries. He suggests several ways that educators can encourage more students to take these courses since they are important to the future generations of managers. One of the ways that is suggested is having textbooks de-emphasize the role of manufacturing in production management. He then calls for the name of the courses to be called ?resource management,? since production has more to do with managing resources.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/254866
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/254866
Y2  - 2026/04/24
